      "summary": "The First World War did not come out of nowhere. Europe before 1914 was a continent of empires, alliances, arms races, and rising nationalism. The big powers — Britain, France, Germany, Austria-Hungary, Russia, and Italy — were competing for influence across Europe and around the world. Industrialization had made armies larger and deadlier, railroads made mobilization faster, and newspapers made international crises feel immediate and dramatic.\n\nBeneath the surface of peace, leaders worried about war, prestige, and security. Germany feared encirclement by France and Russia. Austria-Hungary feared the collapse of its multiethnic empire under nationalist pressure, especially from Slavs in the Balkans. Russia saw itself as the protector of Slavic peoples and wanted influence in southeastern Europe. Britain sought to preserve the balance of power and protect its empire. France wanted security and a way to recover from its defeat by Germany in 1871. All of these tensions made Europe unstable before a single shot was fired in Sarajevo.",
